Class SplitByteArray

  • java.lang.Object
    • com.telenav.kivakit.core.collections.primitive.PrimitiveCollection
      • com.telenav.kivakit.core.collections.primitive.array.PrimitiveArray
        • com.telenav.kivakit.core.collections.primitive.array.PrimitiveSplitArray
          • com.telenav.kivakit.core.collections.primitive.array.scalars.SplitByteArray
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    com.esotericsoftware.kryo.KryoSerializable, ByteCollection, ByteIterable, ByteList, PrimitiveList, Initializable, NamedObject, Countable, Sized, CompressibleCollection
    public final class SplitByteArray
extends PrimitiveSplitArray
implements ByteList
    A split primitive array of byte values. A split array has one key (an index) so it is one-dimensional, although it has an array of children each of which is a primitive array. This is a sort of sparse array that tends to perform well when values cluster by index (which they tend to do with map data identifiers). In addition, allocation of child arrays is quick and memory efficient versus trying to manage one very large array. This design also works around the 2GB limitation of Java arrays (which can only be indexed by int values).

    Supports the operations of ByteCollection, with the exception of PrimitiveCollection.clear(). Indexing operations in ByteList are supported just as in ByteArray, but the values are distributed across an array of child ByteArray objects.

    Author:
    jonathanl (shibo)
    See Also:
    PrimitiveSplitArray, ByteList, ByteArray
